For example:

```aria
// Cast int64 -> int8 (truncates)
int64:x = 257i64;
int8:y = @cast<int8>(x);  // y will be 1 (truncated from 257)

// Cast tbb32 -> tbb8 (clips to min/max of smaller type)  
tbb32:val = -128tbb32;
tbb8:safe = @cast<tbb8>(val);  // safe will be ERR (can't represent -128 in tbb8)
```

The `@` symbol has no special meaning outside of `@cast`; it is simply part of the `@cast` identifier. All other operators use their usual ASCII forms.

